title: For Sale:  1996 Land Rover Discovery
postcontent:
I have a 1996 Land Rover Discovery. It has a 4.0L V8, Automatic Transmission, and 4WD. It has 172k miles. I bought it a couple months ago intending to fix it up a little and keep it, but I recently got an unexpected great deal on a BMW so I dont need the Discovery anymore. I dont need the money, I just dont need the vehicle so Im open to trading as well.

I will take cash or trade for firearm(s) with an appropriate amount of money on either end to balance the deal. Specifically I am looking for an M1A, HK91 (PTR, etc), AR10, AR15, Mossberg pump shotgun, or Ruger LCR-X .357 (exposed hammer), but let me know what you have. I will also take .22, .40, 12ga, or .30-06 ammo.

The Good:
-Starts every time and has never failed to take me where I wanted to go - including off road.
-Comes out of the factory with 4WD and locking differentials. This thing is a beast off road.
-Clean title with no liens ready to sign.
-Aftermarket Speakers and head unit
-Comes with extra set of different factory wheels and tires. This car has a rare wheel lug pattern so wheels are harder to come by. The tires probably have 25% tread life left, and one does not have any air. I dont know if it has a hole or if it just went flat from sitting. They came with the car when I bought it and I have not messed with them.

The Bad:
-Crankshaft position sensor needs replaced eventually. It will occasionally cause a random misfire on one of the cylinders but most of the time it runs normal. I have a new sensor.
-Power steering fluid leak. The seal where the steering wheel shaft goes into the steering box leaks. I have a new steering box.
-Transmission makes a hard shift sometimes. It may be a loose or worn mount or something else. I dont know a thing about automatic transmissions. However it has always shifted at the correct points and never even acted like it didnt want to change gears.
-Fuel Filler vent line is rotted out. Will overflow when filled over 80% full. I have a new hose.

I may replace one or more of those parts this week.

Call me if you have any questions. The car is located in Socorro. I am in Socorro Wed evenings and weekends and I can show it then. title: For Sale:  SALE-CZ VZ50 32CAL PISTOLS W HOLSTERS-$275 EACH
postcontent:
Armed Sources has a pair of CZ VZOR 50 pistols in stock for only $275 EACH. These pistols are in very good condition and come with one mag and a leather holster. 7.65 Browning caliber(32). We will ship to the lower 48 where legal for $25 each. 
Here is a description on the CZ VZOR 50 from world.guns.ru:
The small, pocket-sized Vz.50 was developed during late 1940s for police use and it was chambered for the marginally powerful 7.65x17 Browning ammunition. Apparently influenced by the Walther PP in design, the Vz.50 had several differences in safety and disassembly. In the early 1970s the basic design went through minor face-lift, and the "new" design received the designation of Vz.70. Many Vz.50 pistols were refurbished to Vz.70 standard, with different finish, grip panels and a slightly different safety lever. New Vz.70 pistols were also manufactured between 1970 and 1983. After the replacement in service of the older Vz.50 and Vz.70 by more modern 9mm Vz.82 pistol, most were sold as surplus, as Cz-50 and Cz-70, respectively.

The Vz.50 (commercially sold as Cz-50) is a compact pistol of all-steel construction, firing the relatively weak 7.65mm ammunition. It has a simple blowback action with a fixed barrel. The trigger is double-action, with an exposed hammer and a frame-mounted decocking safety lever. The sights are fixed. Magazines are single stack. The magazine release button is located relatively high on the left side of the frame, behind the trigger. Vz.70 (Cz-70) pistols are similar, with minor differences in the finish, shape of the safety lever and grips. Manual safety is a lever at left side of the frame, behind the trigger guard. To set on safe: pull the lever down; if the hammer was cocked, it will be automatically brought down to rest. To disengage safety: push the lever up; a red dot will appear on the frame.

title: For Sale:  Historical Firearm...Longrifle
postcontent:
Historic piece manufactured between 1849-1853 by legendary Gunsmith Elisha Woods McCraner.

http://www.aolrc.org/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2009/03/vol-vi-no-2-aug-1984.pdf

   pgs 11-12.  McCraner a "Gunsmith" with 5th Reg. US Army in the Mexican War, moved to Ohio after his discharge in 1849. Here J (Jacob) Wilt supplied barrels for McCraner as J Wilt & Co., Dayton, O. until 1853. Both men left their stamp on the barrel of this piece.
Later many of McCraner's rifles were used in the Civil War, in fact this piece was purchased in northern Georgia in the early 1960's. Still later Elisha Woods McCraner custom built a rifle for a young Annie Oakley and her stepfather.  Quite possibly the rifle she used to support her family and possibly the rifle she used during her competition with Butler. "We used two traps, gun below the elbow, one barrel to be used," Annie wrote. "I shot a muzzle-loader, but it was a good one".  

http://www.cincinnati.com/story/news/history/2014/07/20/did-annie-oakley-shooting-contest-happen-in-cincinnati/12913819/

Fired once in the mid 1980's by a gunsmith friend and was said to have "shot straight". 
Stock has a wooden and screw repair that appears to be very old. Hoping it will be added to a collection for it's personality and historical significance.
Contact me for more photo's (this site only allows 3) and additional information.

title: For Sale/Trade:  1 Pint Brownells/ Herters Belgian Blue
postcontent: For Sale/ Trade: 1 Pint Brownells/ Herters Belgian Blue.  Originally developed by Herters, now sold by Brownells who sells it for $43 + $25 hazmat shipping = $68. I’m selling for a very firm $25 - at less than that I'll keep it.  I used enough of this to blue a short pistol barrel, then decided to Duracoat the gun, so 95% or better of the original quantity is still there. An ideal choice for the occasional rebluer who can't afford/doesn't want a hot salts bluing set- up. Applies easily: Clean the gun, boil the metal in water, remove, wipe dry, swab on Belgian Blue, return to the boiling water, then remove and card with fine steel wool. Repeat until the desired color is achieved. Also works pretty good if the metal is just heated with a hair dryer until hot, then swabbed, then washed in hot water. Works on all gun steels except stainless. Instruction sheet included.  Read about it at Brownells website at: http://www.brownells.com/gunsmith-tools-supplies/metal-prep-coloring/metal-bluing/specialty-bluing-chemicals/belgian-blue-prod7604.aspx .  Will ship out of area but HAZMAT shipping will be $25 extra. Will trade for ammo (locally only) if you have what I need.  E-Mail any questions - I don’t do texts.
